      "stimulus_html": "",
      "stem_html": "<p>Bicyclohexadiene, also known as <i>Dewar benzene,</i> is extremely stable despite the fact that its rearrangement to benzene is energetically favored. Explain why the rearrangement is so slow.</p>\n<img class=\"scaled-down-30\" src=\"https://exercises.openstax.org/rails/active_storage/blobs/proxy/eyJfcmFpbHMiOnsibWVzc2FnZSI6IkJBaHBBZzBhIiwiZXhwIjpudWxsLCJwdXIiOiJibG9iX2lkIn19--103d73f8733d45f29c988d95d4771b3f855b2fe3/OChem_30_EC_021.jpg\" alt=\"Dewar benzene (double bonds at C 2 and C 5, with C 1 bonded to C 4 to produce two fused cyclobutene rings) reacts slowly in heat to form benzene.\">",
